				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">You're supposed to handle music <em>after</em> you handle the graphics. This is because the PSG allows writes at any time, not just during blanking.
<br />
<br />If you don't use a register in your NMI handler, you don't need to spend cycles saving and loading it. My NES programs' NMI code typically looks like this:
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">nmi:<br />&nbsp; inc retraces<br />&nbsp; rti<br /></div><br />And then your main loop will look like this:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">forever:<br />&nbsp; jsr read_pads&nbsp; ; read each controller twice and keep readings that agree<br />&nbsp; jsr game_logic&nbsp; ; apply all game rules<br />&nbsp; jsr prepare_ppu&nbsp; ; prepare data to be copied to OAM and VRAM<br />&nbsp; lda retraces<br />:<br />&nbsp; cmp retraces&nbsp; ; wait for NMI handler to signal the start of vblank<br />&nbsp; beq :-<br />&nbsp; jsr update_ppu&nbsp; ; partly-unrolled copies from CPU RAM to tiles, nametables, palette<br />&nbsp; jsr PLAY_ADDR<br />&nbsp; jmp forever<br /></div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

